  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "XfhB9IzDUOAZqBNY+pq10PaOVH4=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "Rather than inlining large manifest JSON into a feed chunk, Connect uses a regenerate-and-publish pattern:\n\n1. Serialize the manifest to a JSON string.\n2. Encrypt it with AES-256-GCM \u2192 encrypted bytes.\n3. Upload to `/bytes` \u2192 receive a 64-char content hash.\n4. Write ONLY the hash to the feed \u2192 a 72-byte SOC (8-byte timestamp + 64-byte reference).\n\nReading reverses the flow: read the feed to get the hash, download the encrypted bytes from `/bytes`, decrypt, and parse JSON.\n\nThis pattern keeps feed writes fast (tiny SOC payloads) and is why feeds are a cheap mutable index over large, otherwise-immutable data. It applies uniformly to document, drive, and user manifests.\n\nThe `SwarmClient` also auto-detects legacy feeds: a feed that contains inline JSON instead of a 64-char hex reference is read with the legacy path for backward compatibility.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z"
    }
  },
